"I was really pleased with this (and how well it held up), as I just got my hands on some Beer Camp bottles. Pored a cloudy, golden hue with little to no head. Looked inviting. Aromas of grapefruit, pineapple, banana/funk, light coriander, and the classic SN bitter note (that I love). Tastes of fruit cup (yeah, that fruit cup), and some orangey citrus. Light Belgian yeasty profile, and nice balance. Classic SN job of absolutely nailing the mouthfeel for the style, and leaving a nice aftertaste. This was my favorite of the Beer Camps I tried. I'd jump on another if I found it."
"Brewed with coriander, Myron’s Walk offers up a faint banana nose, a suggestion of orange, light fruit, spice, malt and a hint of hops. It pours a slight hazy gold under a grand 2” stiff white head that produces classic Belgian gothic window lace. The flavor profile begins with a slight sweetness, banana, faint orange, hints of bubble gum, some biscuit notes and then it dries out with a little yeast funk and an assertive hop bitterness that lingers well into the aftertaste to conclude with a crisp, dry, flavorful finish. The exquisitely creamy, moussey texture gives the beer a satisfying medium to medium light feel."
""
"Pours a hazy golden yellow with a medium white head. Aroma is sweet citrus fruity esters, citrusy hops, mildly bread. Taste is sweet zesty citrus flavor, some spice citrus hops bitterness, yeasty and bread notes. Palate is a medium body, crisp with good carbonation. Finish is sweet fruity flavor, mild zesty spiced citrus hops, yeast with a mild dry hopped bitter ending. Overall a very good, crisp and refreshing brew."
